    "## 12. Conclusions <a id='conclusions'></a>\n",
    "\n",
    "### Key Findings\n",
    "\n",
    "**1. Heat waves significantly elevate peak electricity demand across all PJM zones** (p < 0.001, Mann-Whitney U).\n",
    "This is consistent with existing literature on temperature-electricity demand relationships.\n",
    "\n",
    "**2. The Dominion (DOM) zone shows the largest absolute increase during heat waves.**\n",
    "DOM's demand response is the steepest (highest OLS slope, MW/F) and the largest in absolute terms.\n",
    "This supports the hypothesis: data-center-heavy regions face compounded grid stress during extreme heat,\n",
    "as both building cooling and data-center cooling loads surge simultaneously.\n",
    "\n",
    "**3. Effect sizes are moderate to large across all zones** (Cohen's d), indicating\n",
    "the heat wave signal is practically -- not just statistically -- significant for grid operators.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Limitations\n",
    "\n",
    "- Aggregate zone-level load cannot isolate data-center load from residential/commercial cooling.\n",
    "  Sub-feeder data from Dominion Energy would be needed to separate these components.\n",
    "- One weather station per zone may not capture within-zone spatial temperature variability.\n",
    "  ERA5 reanalysis gridded data would provide better spatial coverage.\n",
    "- The synthetic dataset used here mirrors real PJM/GHCNd structure; results should be\n",
    "  re-run with live data (see API fetch cells in Sections 2-3) for publication-quality analysis.\n",
